"Abstract In testimony before the US Senate Commerce Committee on 25 July 1996, Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) director Louis Freeh, Jr indicated that the Clinton administration might institute encryption import controls if the United States were all of a sudden flooded with imports of non-key escrow encryption products. Freeh also said that if the administration's voluntary key escrow proposals hindered law enforcement's ability to tap encrypted communications, more mandatory controls might have to be instituted domestically. Freeh's comments were in response to questions posed by Senator Conrad Burns, the author of Senate Bill 1726, the Promotion of Commerce Online in the Digital Era Act of 1996 (or Pro-CODE)."
